<div class="content">
    <section>
        <p>
            Recently, one of our data flows that was heavily relying on Postgres,
            started to fail, with the main reason being Postgres going out of
            memory. We decided to scale up our already expensive RDS instance, but
            we quickly realized that, on top being of being expensive, that still
            wasn't enough. It all changed when one of my colleagues suggested to
            update our flow to use the Postgres <span class="keyword">COPY</span>
            command rather than <span class="keyword">INSERT</span> statements.
            The performance improvement was spectacular. In fact, so spectacular,
            that I decided I had to know more about it. This article tells my
            experience with the Postgres <span class="keyword">COPY</span>
            command and summarizes what I've come to learn about it.
        </p>
    </section>
    <section>
        <h3>The problem at hand</h3>
        <p>
            On a regular basis, our backend needs to work out the delta in a
            dataset between two points in time. More specifically, for each
            dataset <span class="datapoint">X</span>, on a regular basis, the
            backend needs to figure out the following:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Which rows left the dataset <span class="datapoint">X</span></li>
            <li>Which rows joined the dataset <span class="datapoint">X</span></li>
            <li>Which rows belonging to the dataset <span class="datapoint">X</span> were updated</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            For example, suppose that at point in time
            <span class="datapoint">t1</span> the dataset
            <span class="datapoint">X</span> contains the following rows:
        </p>
