    <section>
        <h3>The implementation</h3>
        <p>
            To be able to work out the dataset delta as displayed above, the
            backend would keep a separate table, let's call it
            <span class="datapoint">dataset_versions</span>, which would contain
            the entire dataset <span class="datapoint">X</span> as it used to be
            during the last run of our algorithm, at point in time
            <span class="datapoint">t1</span>. At point in time,
            <span class="datapoint">t2</span>, to be able to compute the dataset
            delta, the backend would perform the following tasks:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                Store in <span class="datapoint">dataset_versions</span> the
                entire dataset <span class="datapoint">X</span> as it is at
                point in time <span class="datapoint">t2</span>.
            </li>
            <li>
                Work out insertions, deletions and updates by executing SQL
                queries comparing version <span class="datapoint">t1</span> with
                version <span class="datapoint">t2</span>, both stored in the
                table <span class="datapoint">dataset_versions</span>.
            </li>
            <li>
                Clean up version <span class="datapoint">t1</span> from the table
                <span class="datapoint">dataset_versions</span>. Version
                <span class="datapoint">t2</span> is kept in the table and used
                as the new base version for future delta computations.
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            In other words, the heavy lifting was delegated to the Postgres
            instance managing the table
            <span class="datapoint">dataset_versions</span> and running the
            delta queries.
        </p>
